tool.name: Nicher_SDM

param.name: in_continuous_tifs
param.dialogReference:
One or more GeoTiff raster layers representing continuous-type topographic variables. These are usually unclassified evidence layers such as elevation, slope, aspect, wetness, vegetation greenness, etc.

Note: these layers must be in the GeoTiff format (.tif) and projected in the GDA94 Albers projection (EPSG: 3577).

param.name: in_categorical_tifs
param.dialogReference:
One or more GeoTiff raster layers representing categorical-type topographic variables. These are usually classified evidence layers such as vegetation or soil types with distinct classes.

Note: these layers must be in the GeoTiff format (.tif) and projected in the GDA94 Albers projection (EPSG: 3577).

param.name: out_nc
param.dialogReference: The NetCDF file containing the species distribution model output. This output will always contain x, y coordinates as well as a single variable containing habitat suitability values.

param.name: in_occurrence_feat
param.dialogReference:
A feature layer or shapefile of target occurrence (i.e., presence) points representing known locations of the target phenomenon. It is recommended that all occurrence points should represent one (or very similar) species.

Note: his tool assumes that all points in this input represent target presence (i.e., no absence) and are projected in GDA94 Albers (EPSG: 3577).

param.name: in_num_pseudos
param.dialogReference:
The species distribution model method uses randomly generated points to represent absence locations (called pseudo-absences). Set the number of pseudo-absence points to generate.

Note: set the "equalise number of pseudoabsence points" to on to use the same number as occurrence feature locations.

param.name: in_exclusion_buffer
param.dialogReference:
The size of an exclusion buffer that is generated around occurrence feature locations to prevent pseudoabsence points being generated close to presence areas.

This value is in metres.

param.name: in_equalise_pseudos
param.dialogReference:
Force the number of pseudoabsence points to match the number of input occurrence feature locations.

This can reduce bias when training the species distribution model.

param.name: in_test_ratio
param.dialogReference:
The percentage of occurrence feature locations and pseudoabsence points to be "put aside" specifically for testing model performance.

Note: typically less than 25% (0.25) of the dataset is set aside for training.

param.name: in_resample
param.dialogReference:
If continuous or categorical GeoTiff layer resolutions are inconsistent, all GeoTiffs must be resampled to either the lowest or highest resolution within the set. Set whether to resample to the lowest (e.g., 30m) or highest (e.g., 1m) resolution found.

Note: it is recommended resampling is done to the lowest resolution.

param.name: in_num_estimators
param.dialogReference:
The number of trees in the random forest. Typically a higher value results in a more trustworthy model at the expensive of considerably longer processing time.

Note: the recommended default is 100. Start at 100 and increase to 500, 1000, etc.

See for more details: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier.

param.name: in_criterion
param.dialogReference:
The function to measure the quality of a split. Supported criteria are “gini” for the Gini impurity and “entropy” for the information gain.

Note: Gini is the recommended criterion.

See for more details: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier.

param.name: in_max_depth
param.dialogReference:
The maximum depth of the tree. Leaving this empty ensures that nodes are expanded until all leaves are pure or until all leaves contain less than 1 sample.

Note: Leaving this empty is recommended.

See for more details: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier.

param.name: in_max_features
param.dialogReference:
The number of features to consider when looking for the best split. Two options are provided:

- Auto: maximum number of features is the square root of total number of features

- Log2: maximum number of features is the binary log of total number of features

Note: Auto is recommended.

See for more details: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier.

param.name: in_boostrap
param.dialogReference:
Whether bootstrap samples are used when building trees. If False, the whole dataset is used to build each tree.

Note: Bootstrapping is recommended.

See for more details: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier.

param.name: in_add_result_to_map
param.dialogReference: Whether to visualise the outputs of the tool on the currently active map.

tool.summary:
Nicher predicts the distribution of a target phenomenon's ecological habitat (or niche) based on known occurrence point locations (e.g., field GPS points), GeoTiff layers representing topographic evidence of habitat (e.g., elevation, distance to water, wetness) and machine learning. This process is typically referred to as Species Distribution Modelling (SDM) or Ecological Niche Modelling (ENM).

The target occurrence points can be anything represented as discrete observation points (e.g., flora or fauna observations). GeoTiff layers representing topographic variables can be continuous (e.g., elevation) or classified (e.g., vegetation classes).

The output is a single map representing probability of habitat for the target phenomenon.

Note: occurrence points and topographic variables must be provided by the user. For the latter, the GIS software SAGA is very easy to use and is able to generate dozens of topographic variables from digital elevation model (DEM).

See citation: Booth, T.H., Nix, H.A., Busby, J.R. and Hutchinson, M.F., 2014. BIOCLIM: the first species distribution modelling package, its early applications and relevance to most current MAXENT studies. Diversity and Distributions, 20(1), pp.1-9.
